data.title: Kristin Chenoweth is excited about her new boyfriend, Andrew Pruett
data.meta_description: The blond-haired, blue-eyed couple reportedly met through a mutual friend and they made their official red carpet debut at the Tony Awards Kristin hosted on June 7
data.text:
Kristin Chenoweth is excited about her new boyfriend of three months, Andrew Pruett, who was her date to Monday's Social Life Magazine bash at Town's penthouse at 53 Greene Street in Manhattan.

The 4ft11in Broadway belter - who turns 47 this month - gushed to People that her advertising beau 'is a good man.'

According to his LinkedIn page, Andrew graduated from John Brown University in Arkansas and he's worked for Apple Inc. the last five years in Cupertino.

Scroll down for video

The blond-haired, blue-eyed couple reportedly met through a mutual friend and they made their official red carpet debut at the Tony Awards Kristin hosted on June 7.

Pruett - who used to own a Sonic Drive-In in 1997 - has a six-year-old son Roman with his ex-wife, True Detective's Abigail Spencer.

Before meeting Apple's Global Head of iAd Publisher Relations, Chenoweth dated another single father - two-time Oscar-nominated producer Dana Brunetti (Fifty Shades of Grey, House of Cards).

The triple-threat Tony winner also reportedly romanced former Bachelor star Jake Pavelka, filmmaker Charlie McDowell, Oscar-winning screenwriter Aaron Sorkin, and Tony-nominated thespian Marc Kudisch.

Kristin - born Kristi - will conclude her role as Lily Garland in the revival of On the Twentieth Century this Sunday at Manhattan's American Airlines Theatre.

The Boy Next Door actress will next take on Maleficent in Descendants, which premieres July 31 on the Disney Channel.

The live-action MOW - helmed by Kenny Ortega - centers on the teenage children of Disney's greatest villains as they attend prep school.

'[The] first day of shooting [my onscreen daughter Dove Cameron] started singing to me all of my songs from Wicked and Candide and all the things that I'm sort of known for,' Chenoweth told People.
